# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university-college-london
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The **2010 United Kingdom student protests** were a series of demonstrations in November and December 2010 that took place in several areas of the country, with the focal point of protests being in central London.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Largely student-led, the protests were held in opposition to planned spending cuts to further education and an increase of the cap on tuition fees by the Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition government following their review into higher education funding in England.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Student groups said that the intended cuts to education were excessive, would damage higher education, give students higher debts, and broke campaign promises made by politicians.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The first major demonstration occurred on 10 November, jointly organised by the National Union of Students (NUS) and the University and College Union (UCU).
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] It involved between 30,000 and 50,000 demonstrators marching through central London, with several hundred branching off to attack and occupy the Conservative Party headquarters.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] This measure brought condemnation from the establishment and a divide within the student movement over the appropriateness of such tactics.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The National Campaign Against Fees and Cuts (NCAFC) called for a mass walk-out and demonstration on 24 November, with occupations taking place at campuses throughout the UK.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A march in central London was kettled in Whitehall, resulting in violent confrontation with protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Further demonstrations were held in central London on 30 November, when police clashed with protesters and kettled them in Trafalgar Square, while other protests took place throughout the country.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Another central London protest took place on 9 December, the day that the proposed reforms were passed into law, with protesters clashing with police and being kettled in Parliament Square.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The student protests were unsuccessful in their aim of preventing the government's reforms in England.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] However, in Wales and Northern Ireland, devolved authorities decided not to increase the fees, which led to differing fee levels for the devolved nations.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The demonstrations were highly controversial in the UK, being condemned for instances of violence and vandalism by both the establishment and by protestors.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The behaviour of the Metropolitan Police in dealing with the protests was also widely criticised for alleged instances of untruthfulness and excessive use of force.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In November 2009, the Labour Party government of Prime Minister Gordon Brown commissioned a study into higher education funding in England.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Chaired by Lord Browne of Madingley, the former chief executive of BP, the report was to be titled the Browne Review.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In the build up to the 2010 general election, the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Nick Clegg, pledged that he would vote against any proposed increase in tuition fees if elected to Parliament.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Following the election and resulting hung parliament, Clegg made an agreement with the Conservative Party to form a coalition government in which Conservative leader David Cameron became Prime Minister and Clegg became Deputy Prime Minister.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The Browne Review was subsequently published in October 2010, and contained the suggestion that the government should remove outright the existing cap of £3,290 on tuition fees.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The government rejected this proposal, instead choosing to keep a cap but increasing it to £9,000.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] David Willetts, the Minister of State for Universities and Science, stated that the measures were "a very progressive package" and "at the end of this we will have a better university system than we have at the moment".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Contravening his pre-election pledge, Clegg expressed support for the rise in the cap on tuition fees, which would result in future students paying higher fees for their university education.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Student union leaders were critical of the cuts.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The National Union of Students (NUS) feared that the increased cap on tuition fees would prevent potential students from poorer backgrounds from attending university.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Many protesters focused in particular on Clegg's campaign promise that he would oppose any rise in tuition fees.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Two weeks before, on 28 October, a protest was held in the University of Oxford to coincide with a visit from the Liberal Democrat minister and Business Secretary Vince Cable.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Cable cancelled his visit after taking advice from the police about the protest.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Several days later, on 3 November, there was a student protest in Dublin.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The subsequent London protest was described by one Irish reporter as "scenes bizarrely similar" to those in the Irish capital.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The initial event was the largest student protest in Britain since the Labour government first proposed the Teaching and Higher Education Act in 1998.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The first major demonstration in protest at the government's proposed reforms was held on 10 November 2010 in central London, jointly organised by the National Union of Students (NUS) and the University and College Union (UCU).
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] This demonstration was officially known as "Fund Our Future: Stop Education Cuts", although also termed "Demo 2010" or "Demo-lition 10.11.10".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Arriving from all regions of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, approximately 30,000 to 52,000 protesters attended the demonstration.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Political groups that sent contingents to take part included the Labour Party, Plaid Cymru, the Green Party, Socialist Workers Party, Socialist Party, Revolution, Young Communist League, Revolutionary Communist Group, and Communist Students.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A few members of parliament (MPs) joined the demonstration, among them Labour MP John McDonnell, who told reporters: "This is the biggest workers' and students' demonstration in decades.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] It just shows what can be done when people get angry.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Representatives of the National Pensioners Convention also took part, with the group's banner carrier, Janet Shapiro, stating that: "We're here because we believe education should be free, funded by the taxpayer.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Hunt stated that making the public university system in Britain "the most expensive in the world" was unfair, that discouraging young people from going to college was not progressive, and that the increase in tuition fees represented further debts for students.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The rally was also addressed by NUS President Aaron Porter and the Trades Union Congress Deputy general secretary Frances O'Grady.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] O'Grady offered the message to the government that: "Don't you dare tell us we're all in this together.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The deficit certainly wasn't caused by the students." The protest was scheduled to end at 2 pm, but slightly overran.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police were expecting 20,000 demonstrators to turn out, well below the 50,000 figure most widely quoted in the press after the event, and did not expect any violence, so deployed only 225 officers to police the event.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In the afternoon, as protesters passed the Houses of Parliament and moved towards Tate Britain for the rally, several thousand surrounded 30 Millbank in Westminster, campaign headquarters of the Conservative Party, despite attempts by NUS organisers to stop them.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Forcing their way past the limited police presence, approximately 200 people broke in and occupied the building, whilst a thousand more cheered and supported them from outside.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] These protesters lit placards on fire, and smashed windows before occupying and vandalising the reception area.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Staff working in the building were evacuated by police around 1 pm.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Around 100 protesters proceeded to the roof of the building, chanting slogans including "Greece!
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Initial press sources blamed this action on a group of anarchists.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] This was later disputed, with a reporter from *The Guardian* noting that most of the protesters occupying the building were students who had been radicalised in opposition to the cuts, and were not all political anarchists.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Riot police from the Territorial Support Group arrived an hour after the building was occupied to remove the protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In retaliation, the police were pelted with eggs, rotten fruit, banners, and shards of glass.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] One of the protesters on the building's roof, Edward Woolard, threw a fire extinguisher onto the police below.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] He received instant criticism from some of the protesting crowds, who called on those on the roof to "stop throwing shit".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] To control the situation, police used the controversial technique of kettling to trap the protesters within Millbank Square, the forecourt to 30 Millbank, whilst protesters on the outside of the building were pushed back.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The police began letting demonstrators out of the building from 6:30 pm, arresting those whom they believed were responsible for vandalism.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In all, 14 people were injured and required hospitalisation, at least three of whom were police officers, whilst police arrested 35 of the demonstrators, sending them off to various police stations around the city.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Later accounts that the numbers arrested had risen to 54, (33 men and 21 women), ten of whom were aged under 18 and the majority of whom were students.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The actions of a minority, out of 50,000 people, is regrettable." Oxford University's Student Union (OUSU) President David Barclay issued a statement declaring that "OUSU supports the rights of students to protest non-violently.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Contrastingly, other student leaders, trade unionists, and academics expressed support for elements of the occupation of 30 Millbank.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Meanwhile, various university Conservative societies around London condemned the protests, and criticised students' unions for providing the "false impression that the majority of students are left-wing" and opposed to the governments' proposed reforms.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police Service admitted that they were unprepared to deal with the occupation of 30 Millbank, something which they had not been expecting.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Sir Paul Stephenson, the Metropolitan Police's Commissioner, told the press that he was "embarrassed" by how police had lost control of the situation, and condemned what he saw as "thuggish, loutish behaviour by criminals".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Stephenson remarked that "the one thing I would say is that it must have been an awful time for the people trying to go about their daily business in those buildings.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] I feel terribly sorry that they have had to go through what must have been quite a traumatic experience...
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] We are determined to make sure that sort of thing does not happen again on our streets.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] I'm clear on that, the Met is clear on that." His views were echoed by Mayor of London Boris Johnson, who stated: "This is intolerable and all those involved will be pursued and they will face the full force of the law...
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police commissioner has assured me that there will be a vigorous post-incident investigation.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Prime Minister David Cameron condemned the occupation of Millbank, stating that he would not abandon his position on the issue of education cuts.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Speaking from the 2010 G20 Seoul summit in South Korea, Cameron said the occasion had been "extremely serious" and praised the "bravery" of the police officers.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] He also stated that the actions of the protesters were "unacceptable" and that "I was worried for the safety of the people in the building because I know people who work there".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The following morning, Clegg went on ITV's *Daybreak* to state: "I should have been more careful perhaps in signing that pledge [to not increase tuition fees]...
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At the time [prior to his election] I really thought we could do it.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The *Financial Times* reported that an anonymous vice-chancellor from a London university had told them that the violence would undermine the campaign, and that it "could not have gone better for the government.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In the following days, smaller protests were held in Manchester and Cambridge, with no violent confrontations.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] On 11 November, student protesters occupied a building at the University of Manchester for three hours, demanding to see the accounts that discussed how government funding cuts would affect students.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Between 60 and 100 students held a peaceful sit-in at Manchester's John Owens Building on Oxford Road after an NUS meeting earlier that day.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Representing this group, protester Jeremy Buck said: "This is just what a few students who had the energy left after the London demo managed to achieve...
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Imagine what will happen when they have enough time to organise properly for the 24th.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] It is a matter of watch this space." That same day, protesters at the University of Cambridge held a demonstration against the cuts at the university's annual science, engineering and technology careers fair.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] On 23 November, anti-education cuts protesters had assembled outside of the offices of *The Guardian* newspaper, where Clegg was giving his Hugo Young lecture.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] They brought out an effigy of Clegg, sentencing it to death and executing it by hanging, shouting the slogan "Nick Clegg, shame on you, shame on you for turning blue".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A second significant demonstration took place in London on 24 November, which again led to clashes with police, this time outside Whitehall, after police kettled a large crowd.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] An organisation known as the National Campaign Against Fees and Cuts (NCAFC) organised a mass national walk-out of education and protest for 24 November.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] As a part of this, demonstrations were held in London and other locations across the United Kingdom.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The NCAFC encouraged protesters to use social media to invite others to join them.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Several thousand protesters, most of whom were students or school children, gathered in Trafalgar Square, central London, late in the morning.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] They proceeded toward Whitehall shouting the slogan, "fuck David Cameron".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Believing that there had been a lack of officers at 10 November demonstration, the Metropolitan Police drafted in 1000 police officers from across Greater London to oversee the event, almost five times the number at 10 November.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Police informed press that they planned to monitor fringe elements within the demonstration whom they believed planned to encourage "vandalism and violence".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At Whitehall, just before 1 pm, police prevented the protesters from reaching Parliament Square and the Houses of Parliament, setting up a line of riot police to kettle the protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A reporter *The Guardian* described the crowd at this point as being "predominantly good natured, although very noisy".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Nonetheless, the demonstrators tried to push through the police line, leading to clashes.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] An unoccupied police van which had been left in the midst of the crowd was vandalised; protesters rocked it back and forth, climbed on its roof, smashed its windows, wrote graffiti on it and threw a smoke bomb inside.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A group of school girls encircled the van, urging people not to vandalise it.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At around 6 pm, mounted police charged at the north end of the crowd to push them back; despite video evidence police denied that this was an actual charge, describing it as crowd control using horses.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Various bus shelters and ticket machines in the area were vandalised, with Transport for London diverting buses away from the unrest.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Approximately 200 protesters were unable to escape and remained kettled in Whitehall.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Police falsely informed press that the crowd were provided with toilet facilities and water; protesters disputed these claims on social media, with ULU President Clare Solomon commenting on Facebook: "we're still illegally kettled in the freezing cold on Whitehall.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] No food, water or toilets despite what the police are telling the media.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Thousands of young people needing to go home." To keep warm, protesters set fire to a ticket machine within the Square, prompting riot police to secure the machine and put out the flames.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] From 9 to 10 pm, police permitted the rest of the Whitehall protesters to leave, approximately nine to ten hours after they had first been contained, some being searched as they left.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] During the clashes, police arrested 41 protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Across the UK, protesters occupied university buildings in at least 12 universities.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] On 23 November, protesters occupied the picture gallery corridor of Royal Holloway, University of London.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] They were later joined by supportive members of university staff who took part in what was labelled a "teach-in".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] On 24 November, the Language Centre at London South Bank University was occupied for 51 hours by over 100 students as part of the "Defend LSBU!
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] They're quoting Harry Potter rather than Che Guevara." Protesters also occupied the University of East London, demanding that university managers "put pressure on the government on the issue of H[higher] E[ducation] cuts and tuition fee rises".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A group of about 100 occupied a lecture theatre in the Roscoe Building.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At the University of Oxford, students initially occupied the Radcliffe Camera.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At the University of Cambridge, 200 students scaled the fence of Senate House and marched onto the grounds of King's College, then on 26 November students started an 11-day occupation of part of Old Schools, the main administrative block of the university.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At the University of Bristol, 2000 protesters clashed with police when they tried to move into the city centre.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In Brighton, 3000 demonstrators marched through the city, with nearly 50 occupying a university building.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Hundreds of students from Kingston University and various local schools staged an impromptu march through the town and a sit down protest at College Roundabout, leading to one arrest.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Hundreds of them had walked out of the local Allerton Grange High School to join the demonstration, and later occupied the Michael Sadler lecture theatre and a room at Leeds Metropolitan University.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A room at the University of Plymouth was also occupied.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At Cardiff University, around 200 protesters occupied a lecture theatre after failing to gain entry to the vice-chancellor's building.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] During the Whitehall incident, the Metropolitan Police publicly defended their use of kettling, with Chief Inspector Jane Connors claiming that they had only used it as "a last resort".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At a meeting of the Metropolitan Police Authority the following day, the Metropolitan Police's Commissioner Sir Paul Stephenson defended the tactics.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] He was criticised by Jenny Jones, a Green Party member of the London Assembly, who told him: "when you imprison thousands of people, which is essentially what you did yesterday, you do have a duty of care to them...
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] You kept people for nine-and-a-half hours.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A spokesperson for Prime Minister Cameron stated that "people have a right to engage in lawful and peaceful protest, but there is no place for violence or intimidation", while education minister David Willetts responded by claiming that protesting students did not understand the government's plans.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Clegg stated on BBC Radio 2 that "I hate in politics, as in life, to make promises that you then find you can't keep.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] We made a promise we can't deliver – we didn't win the election outright and there are compromises in coalition." Labour Party leader Ed Miliband stated that he would not rule out joining further demonstrations, remarking that "I was quite tempted to go out and talk to them [the protesters].
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Peaceful demonstrations are part of our society.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A third central London protest was organised for Tuesday 30 November, a day that saw cold temperatures and snow in the city.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Protesters assembled at Trafalgar Square, but a police line prevented their march down Whitehall towards the Houses of Parliament; the NCAFC accused the Police of "pre-emptively block[ing]" the protest route.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Fearing that they would be kettled in the Square, protesters dispersed throughout the city center, pursued by police.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Other officers stood photographing and filming the students for later identification, while police vans blocked off certain streets.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Some protesters chanted "Peaceful protest!
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Peaceful protest!" and "no ifs, no buts, no education cuts", and others blew vuvuzelas and played reggae from portable stereo systems.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A BBC reporter talked to members of the demonstration, noting that while many desired a peaceful outcome, others believed that violent confrontation with the police was inevitable.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Many were angry with how they had been portrayed in the media, with one commenting that confrontation was not caused by "hardcore anarchists" but by "students who are very, very angry".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Many protesters ran onto Pall Mall and then past St James's Park.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Denied access to Parliament Square by police, they turned around and headed toward Westminster Abbey.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A reporter from *The Guardian* noted that "the march is fracturing – people are going up different streets and getting lost.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The police kettled those in the Square, whilst some of the protesters waved banners with slogans such as "Don't put the kettle on, Mr.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Cameron" and "I Can't Believe It's Not Thatcher".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The police "put lines [of officers] across all the exits" to the kettled area of the Square, but reportedly allowed small groups of protesters to leave, even though the majority, around 150 to 200, decided to stay and continue protesting in the snow.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Some protesters burned placards and one spray-painted the word "Revolution" on Nelson's Column.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Others threw plastic bottles and fireworks at police lines, and at one point there "was a scuffle as a knot of policemen rushed one of the protesters, grabbing him to arrest him, and the crowd flocked angrily to the area".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At another time, a group of riot police moved into the crowd of protesters to attempt to secure Nelson's Column, only to be surrounded by demonstrators shouting "Who's kettling who?
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] We're kettling you!" Other slogans shouted at police during the protest included "Shame on you!" and "Your job's next".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Police then arrested 146 demonstrators who refused to leave the Square; 139 of them were arrested for breach of the peace, whilst seven were arrested on suspicion of violent disorder.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Seven more had been arrested in central London earlier in the day.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The night before, on 28 November, a crowd of two to three hundred protesters gathered outside of Lewisham Town Hall in Catford, south London, where a council meeting was then in progress, to protest against wider public sector cuts.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Several Youtube videos of the incident were shown on national news, including the BBC.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Many of the protesters had come from nearby sixth forms (due to potential Education Maintenance Allowance cuts) and also from Goldsmiths College.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Demonstrators, playing music and political slogans from boomboxes forced their way into the building, where a smoke bomb was let off, while another protester climbed onto the roof and unfurled a banner.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Several more flares were set off outside and windows smashed, with riot police from the Territorial Support Group close by, were called and several arrests were made.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] One of the protesters, Sue Luxton, a former Green Party councillor who had subsequently become a teacher, told the press that "I wanted to peacefully express my anger at the cuts...
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] On the day of the main demonstration, there were also further protests across the United Kingdom, including in Cardiff, Cambridge, Colchester, Newcastle, Bath, Leeds, Sheffield, Edinburgh, Liverpool, Belfast, Brighton, York, Manchester, Plymouth, Scunthorpe and Bristol.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] About 1,500 students, including school children, took part in the protest in Brighton, whilst protests in Bristol involved police being pelted with mustard and ten demonstrators were arrested.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In Sheffield, police were pelted with snowballs as they guarded the constituency office of Nick Clegg from a crowd of two hundred protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The British protests coincided with those in Italy, where demonstrations occurred in Milan, Turin, Naples, Venice, Palermo, Bari, Genoa, and Rome where riot police were called in to prevent students from gaining access to the parliament building.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Meanwhile, whilst occupations that had begun the previous week continued at University College London, Newcastle University and the University of Cambridge, a new one began at the University of Nottingham, where 150 protesters occupied a building.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] University buildings and local government buildings were occupied in Birmingham and Oxford while police blocked an attempt at occupation of the council building in York.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The protesters occupying the council chamber in Birmingham left after four hours, with a police spokesperson commending the protesters for their "wholly peaceful" behaviour, and noting that it "couldn't have been more different from the violent clashes seen recently in London".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] ULU members handed out green hard hats with the words "Tax the banks, not the students" on them, whilst a rally was held in Bloomsbury at midday, where ULU President Solomon addressed the crowd.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police had positioned lines of riot police and police vans along the Houses of Parliament, to prevent any protesters gaining access to it.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Superintendent Julia Pendry issued a statement saying: "Protesters will be allowed sight and sound of parliament.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] However, there is evidence to suggest a number of people will come to London intent on causing violence and disorder.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The protesters marched from Bloomsbury to Parliament Square in the afternoon, where they pushed down metal barriers and occupied the Square.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Around 3:30 pm, police kettled those several thousand protesters in the square, preventing them from leaving, stating that it was necessary "due to the level of violence that our officers are facing".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Mounted police charged into the crowd on one side of the Square in an attempt to disperse them.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A field hospital was set up on the green providing emergency first aid to protesters as well as tea and food within the containment area.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Around 30 protesters were treated, most for head injuries.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Police used batons to hit protesters, and a St John Ambulance member told press that he had treated ten protesters for head injuries from being struck by police batons by 4.30 pm.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] One protester, philosophy student Alfie Meadows, suffered a blow to the head from a police truncheon that knocked him unconscious.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Taken to hospital, it was discovered that he was suffering from bleeding of the brain, and required brain surgery.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Reporter Jonathan Haynes of *The Guardian*, who was present, characterised the police tactics as "very heavy handed".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Police informed press that they were allowing young and vulnerable protesters to leave the kettle, but those inside the kettle, including journalists, asserted that this was untrue.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At 5:41 pm, news reached the protesters that the government had voted to support the proposals.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Clashes ensued between the crowd and the police, and the protesters pulled along metal fencing to separate themselves from riot police, who were trying to push them all into the centre of the Square.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Later on in the evening, with the protesters still kettled in the Square, protesters smashed all of the windows on the ground floor of Her Majesty's Treasury.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] At 21:15, the protest was forced onto Westminster Bridge where it was kettled until approximately 23:30.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Due to the Parliament Square protest being kettled, many other demonstrators could not enter the Square and so disseminated across much of the rest of central London.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Meanwhile, many of those students who remained around the area of Trafalgar Square continued to protest, with about 150 holding a sit-in in the adjacent National Gallery, while others attempted to set fire to the Trafalgar Square Christmas tree.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] During the protests, a car taking The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall to the evening's Royal Variety Performance at the London Palladium was attacked on Regent Street and Home Secretary Theresa May confirmed a protester 'made contact' with Camilla.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In Oxford Street, Topshop was damaged, as rioters sprayed "pay your tax" on the building and broke windows.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Home Secretary Theresa May issued a statement in which she "utterly condemned" the actions of the protesters, and declared that "What we are seeing in London tonight, the wanton vandalism, smashing of windows, has nothing to do with peaceful protest...
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Nearly 50 people complained to the Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) about police behaviour during the various protests held around the country, with the majority directed against the Metropolitan Police, including complaints of violence used against protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Following the protests, video footage posted on YouTube showed Jody McIntyre, a protester with cerebral palsy, involved in an altercation with police.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The footage showed McIntyre, who had positioned himself in the front line facing police, being pulled out of his wheelchair and dragged across the ground by Metropolitan Police officers.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] While McIntyre later said he had been pulled out of the wheelchair twice, only one incident is shown in the video.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] On 13 December, he was interviewed about the incident by BBC journalist Ben Brown, an interview later described by *The Guardian* newspaper as "having a distinct lack of sympathy from the BBC" and it was noted that the incident had "attracted thousands of complaints".
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] McIntyre's complaint was later rejected by Scotland Yard.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] His subsequent appeal was partly upheld by the IPCC.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Street medics treated student protesters during the parliament square protest on Thursday 9 December, the day of the scheduled vote to raise university tuition fees.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] A field tent was set up on the green providing emergency first aid to protesters as well as tea and food within the containment area.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Alfie Meadows was acquitted of all charges in 2013.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In September 2023 the Metropolitan Police apologised to him and agreed a financial settlement.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] On 30 November, following the third main day of protesting, the Welsh Assembly announced that it would not permit an increase in fees for Welsh students.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In July 2011, three school children will challenge the kettling of children at the 24 November 2010 protest.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In September 2011, students in Northern Ireland succeeded in getting the Northern Ireland Assembly to freeze tuition fees, avoiding the large fee increases in England.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Student leaders in Northern Ireland cited the wider protests across the UK as one reason for their success.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] As of 2020, this has saved Northern Ireland university students £1 billion in tuition fees compared to English students.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In November 2012, two years after the 2010 demonstrations, protests ignited again from the student movement.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Organised by the NUS, around 10,000 demonstrators marched in central London.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] Cooper complained that the allegations were untrue, threatened his future academic prospects and left his reputation "as badly trashed" as the Millbank Tower.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The years following the student protests saw a leftward shift in the politics of the NUS.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] In 2014 the NUS Conference voted in support of free education, reversing the union's previous policy of advocating a graduate tax as a replacement for tuition fees, which it had adopted in the late 2000s.
[src:university-college-london/2010-uk-student-protests] The Student Broad Left made progressive gains in the mid-2010s, culminating in the election of SBL candidate Malia Bouattia as NUS President.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] During the Gaza war and genocide, protests on university campuses in solidarity with the Palestinians in Gaza escalated in April 2024, spreading in the United States and other countries, as part of wider Gaza war protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The escalation, nicknamed by activists the "student intifada", began on April 18 after mass arrests at the Gaza Solidarity Encampment at Columbia University, in which protesters demanded the university's disinvestment from Israel.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Over 3,100 protesters were arrested in the U.S., including faculty members and professors, on over 60 campuses.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests spread across Europe in May with mass arrests in the Netherlands, 20 encampments established in the United Kingdom, and across universities in Australia and Canada.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The different protests' varying demands included severing financial ties with Israel, transparency about financial ties, ending partnerships with Israeli institutions, and amnesty for protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Universities suspended and expelled student protesters, in some cases evicting them from campus housing.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many universities relied on police to forcibly disband encampments and end occupations of buildings, several made agreements with protesters for encampments to be dismantled, and others cut ties with Israeli institutions or companies involved with Israel and its occupied territories.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The campus occupations also resulted in the closure of Columbia University, Cal Poly Humboldt, and the University of Amsterdam; rolling strikes by academic workers on campuses in California, and the cancellation of some U.S. university graduation ceremonies.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Hundreds of groups expressed support for the protests, and the police response in the U.S. was criticised.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Supporters of Israel and some Jewish students raised concerns about antisemitic incidents at or around the protests, prompting condemnations of the protests by international leaders.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students and faculty members who participated in the protests, many of whom are Jewish, said the protests were not antisemitic.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A May 2024 poll estimated that 8% of U.S. college students had participated in the protests, with 45% supporting them and 24% opposed.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 97% of the protests remained nonviolent and 28–40% of Americans supported the protests with 42–47% opposed.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests were compared to the anti-Vietnam and 1968 protests, politically criticized by a wide range of mainstream U.S.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Republican and Democratic politicians, and frequently counter-protested by Zionist and right-wing organizations.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests, including rallies, demonstrations, campaigns, and vigils related to the Gaza war occurred across the U.S. since the conflict's start on October 7, 2023, alongside other Gaza war protests around the world.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian protesters criticized Israel's invasion, war conduct in the Gaza Strip, and U.S. military and diplomatic support for Israel.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students occupying administrative buildings were arrested at the request of college administrators at Brown University in November and December 2023, and at Pomona College on April 5, 2024.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In March 2024, after protesters occupied the president's office at Vanderbilt University, the university suspended students and expelled three.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] These were "believed to be the first student expulsions over protests related to the Israel-Hamas conflict", according to *The New York Times*.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which was established to protect against racial discrimination in Jim Crow laws affecting education, was reinterpreted by Attorney Kenneth L.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Marcus while he was working at the Office for Civil Rights of the United States Department of Education to include protections against discrimination on the basis of religion, particularly "when an affected student's 'shared ancestry' would have been treated as a 'race' in earlier jurisprudence".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Jason Brownlee writes that Marcus "subsequently became one of the preeminent advocates for applying Title VI against speech and events criticizing Israeli repression of Palestinians, deeds Marcus considered antisemitic", and advocated adopting the IHRA definition of antisemitism.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On October 25, 2023, Jonathan Greenblatt of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) and Alyza D.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Administrators at several private universities then suspended their SJP chapters, starting with Brandeis University on November 6, 2023.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On November 14, Columbia University followed suit, and also suspended its chapter of Jewish Voice for Peace.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The state of Florida ordered that all SJP chapters in the state be disbanded.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 6, 2024, student protests had occurred in 45 of the 50 states in the United States and the District of Columbia, with encampments, occupations, walkouts or sit-ins on almost 140 campuses.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Thirty-four encampments were established in the United Kingdom; across universities in Australia, beginning with the University of Sydney; and in Canada, including an encampment at McGill University.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 7, protests spread further on European campuses after mass arrests at the University of Amsterdam campus occupation, including occupation of campus buildings at Leipzig University in Germany, Sciences Po in France, and Ghent University in Belgium.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 8, protests had taken place in more than 25 countries, and on May 13, approximately 1,000 Dutch students and university staff took part in a national walk-out.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A series of occupation protests by pro-Palestinian students occurred at Columbia University in New York City from April to June 2024, in the context of the broader Gaza war protests in the United States.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests began on April 17, 2024, when pro-Palestinian students established an encampment of approximately 50 tents on campus, calling it the Gaza Solidarity Encampment, and demanded that the university divest from Israel.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The first encampment was dismantled when university president Minouche Shafik authorized the New York City Police Department (NYPD) to enter the campus on April 18 and conduct mass arrests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A new encampment was built the next day.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The administration then entered into negotiations with protesters, which failed on April 29 and resulted in the suspension of student protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The next day, protesters broke into and occupied Hamilton Hall, leading to a second NYPD raid, the arrest of more than 100 protesters, and the full dismantling of the camp.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The arrests marked the first time Columbia had allowed police to suppress campus protests since the 1968 demonstrations against the Vietnam War.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 31, a third campus encampment was briefly established in response to an alumni reunion.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Other colleges that had encampments are marked in green, and non-encampment protests are marked in blue.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests emerged throughout the U.S. in the following days, with protest camps established on over 40 campuses.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 25, mass arrests occurred at Emerson College, the University of Southern California, and the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A continued crackdown on April 27 led to approximately 275 arrests at Washington, Northeastern, Arizona State, and Indiana University Bloomington.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Several professors were among those detained at Emory University, and at Washington University in St.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Louis, university employees were arrested.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 28, counter-protests were held at MIT, the University of Pennsylvania, and the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA).
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 30, approximately 300 protesters were arrested at Columbia University and City College of New York and pro-Israel counter-protesters attacked the UCLA campus occupation.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The next day, over 200 arrests were made at UCLA.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Hundreds of arrests ensued in May, notably at the Art Institute of Chicago, University of California, San Diego, the Fashion Institute of Technology in New York, and University of California, Irvine.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 20, the first strike by academic workers took place on campuses in California at UC Santa Cruz, followed by UC Davis and UCLA on May 28.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests ended as universities closed for the summer.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many of the protests involved students demanding that their schools sever financial ties to Israel and companies involved in the conflict, as well as an end to U.S. military support for Israel, as part of the Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions (BDS) movement.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some protests also demanded that universities sever academic ties with Israel, support a ceasefire in Gaza, and disclose investments.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Student demands varied among the different occupations, including that universities stop accepting research money from Israel that supports the military, and that college endowments stop investing with managers who profit from Israeli entities.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Student protesters called on Columbia University to financially divest from any company with business ties to the Israeli government, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] NYU Alumni for Palestine called on New York University to "terminate all vendor contracts with companies playing active roles in the military occupation in Palestine and ongoing genocide in Gaza, namely Cisco, Lockheed Martin, Caterpillar and General Electric".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian protesters demanded that the University of Washington cut ties with Boeing.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at the University of Vermont demanded the cancellation of a planned commencement speech by Linda Thomas-Greenfield.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] After several mass arrests, the demands also included amnesty for students and faculty who were disciplined or fired for protesting.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests on many campuses were created by coalitions of student groups, and largely independent, although Reuters Press reported that they were inspired by demonstrations at Columbia University.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters at Vanderbilt University smashed a window and injured a security guard.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In April 2024, the occupations resulted in the closure of Columbia University and Cal Poly Humboldt for the remainder of the semester, and faculty members in California, Georgia, and Texas also initiated votes of no confidence.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Columbia, Cal Poly Humboldt, and the University of Southern California canceled their graduation ceremonies due in May.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 13, the University of Amsterdam closed for two days after renewed occupations on campus.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] After demands from protesters, the University of Vermont canceled its graduation ceremony speaker, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations Linda Thomas-Greenfield.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On June 1, students staged a walkout at the University of Chicago's graduation ceremony, and walkouts at graduations occurred at Harvard University, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and elsewhere.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In April, a pro-Palestinian student group won elections in the University of Michigan's student government.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In August, the student government voted to freeze its funding for student clubs until the university met student activists' divestment demands.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 28, Portland State University (PSU) announced it was pausing its financial ties with Boeing, including gifts and grants, over its ties to Israel.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] PSU President Ann Cudd wrote in a campus-wide letter, "the passion with which these demands are being repeatedly expressed by some in our community motivates".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 6, Trinity College Dublin in Ireland agreed to end its investments in Israeli companies that are listed on the United Nations Human Rights Council "blacklist" after an encampment on Fellows' Square was erected.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] This included three of the 13 Israeli companies the university's endowment fund had invested in.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The University of Helsinki in Finland suspended student exchanges with Israeli universities on May 21 after two weeks of campus protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 28, the University of Copenhagen in Denmark announced it would cease investing in companies that operate in the occupied West Bank, divesting US$145,810 worth of holdings from Airbnb, Booking.com, and EDreams the next day.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Three days later, Ghent University in Belgium cut ties with Israeli universities and research institutions, referencing "concerns regarding connections between Israeli academic institutions and the Israeli government, military, or security services".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The university had severed ties with three Israeli institutions two weeks earlier, citing incompatibility with Israel's human rights policy.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On June 11, the University of Waterloo in Ontario, Canada, agreed to protesters' demands to factor human rights into its investment decisions.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In late August 2024, San Francisco State University began the divestment process from four weapons manufacturers involved with the war.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The next month, the MIT Coalition for Palestine announced that MIT would discontinue its MIT-Lockheed Martin Seed Fund, a program that financed collaboration between MIT and Israeli universities.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The Coalition said this was "the first known American-Israeli weapons manufacturer partnership to end at an American university since the war on Gaza began".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Three months later, the Institut d'études politiques de Strasbourg said it would break ties with Reichman University in Israel due to its "warmongering" stance on Gaza.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Other universities said they would consider divestment demands regarding Israel-affiliated companies.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some agreed to disclose their investments and committed to increase awareness about Palestine.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Wesleyan University allowed encampments on campus to continue, and at the University of Barcelona, the Senate voted to break ties with Israel.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 15, the protest encampment at Harvard University ended after the administration agreed to discuss the protesters' demands and to rescind the suspension of 20 students.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At California State University, Sonoma State campus president Mike Lee was placed on leave after he agreed to pursue divestment from Israel "without the appropriate approvals".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 23, the University of Sydney became the first Australian university to accept certain demands.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The university agreed to further disclose research grants, subject to confidentiality requirements, in order to increase transparency.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at The New School attempted a unique strategy that combined escalations at their encampment and negotiations with administrators.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Rather than accepting that negotiations could continue only if escalation ceased, organizers escalated their protests and then offered to cease that escalation in exchange for other concessions during negotiations, improving their bargaining position.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Though police ultimately swept their encampment, the sweep led to backlash and condemnation by faculty and deans and required a day-long shutdown of the campus.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at The New School secured the formation of an advisory investment committee and a subsequent trustee vote on investment in the fall.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The authorization did not guarantee a strike, but allowed the executive board to call one at any time.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Strike action began at UC Santa Cruz on May 20.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Union members and leaders said they were not teaching or grading, were withholding data, and would continue to do so until they reached a deal with university officials.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The strike was in part a protest against arrests of pro-Palestinian protesters at UCLA, UC Irvine, and UC San Diego.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The UC system responded by seeking an injunction against the union, declaring the walkout illegal.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 23, the California Public Employment Relations Board denied the injunction.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The walkout extended to UCLA and UC Davis on May 28, with the intention of expanding to UC Santa Barbara, UC San Diego, and UC Irvine starting the week of June 3.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Participants included students, faculty, and unaffiliated people of various backgrounds, including Jews and Muslims.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian activists at Columbia said their movement is anti-Zionist, and several campus protests were organized by anti-Zionist groups.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some of the protests were organized by groups such as Students for Justice in Palestine (SJP), Jewish Voice for Peace, IfNotNow, and the Young Democratic Socialists of America.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters also identified a wide range of other ideologies that motivated them, such as anti-racism, intersectionality, anti-colonialism, anti-imperialism, police and prison abolitionism, eco-socialism, indigenous rights, and freedom of expression.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters also criticized President Joe Biden and his administration's support for Israel.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] As part of the occupations, protesters hosted teach-ins, interfaith prayer, and musical performances.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some protests invited people to tour or speak, such as Palestinian photojournalist Motaz Azaiza, who was invited to and visited Columbia's protest.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The Palestinian activist Linda Sarsour said, "These young people are reaffirming and demonstrating that the tide is shifting on Palestine, that the Palestinian people have solidarity not just across the United States of America, but across the world".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At Columbia, protesters who breached Hamilton Hall wrote revolutionary slogans (e.g., "Political power comes from the barrel of a gun") on blackboards.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] One group involved in the protest movement, Columbia University Apartheid Divest, grew more supportive of armed resistance led by Hamas and the October 7 attacks over the course of 2024.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Within Our Lifetime leader Nerdeen Kiswani, who arrived at the Columbia encampment in April, called for Palestine liberation "'by any means necessary', including armed resistance".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Her group formed from CUNY SJP, which targeted the Brooklyn Museum in May 2024.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many anti-Zionist protesters donned masks and keffiyehs, which increased concerns from provosts and deans that outsiders had infiltrated protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters expressed fears of receiving reputational and professional harm from identification.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Concern was raised about the presence of outside groups at protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] During arrests in New York on May 2, police announced that nearly half of those arrested at Columbia and CCNY were unaffiliated with either school.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Mayor Eric Adams said that they had seen evidence that outside agitators and "professionals" such as Lisa Fithian and the wife of Sami Al-Arian had given students tactical knowledge and training to escalate their protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A University of Texas at Austin official said half of the rule breakers detained at a protest on April 24, 2024, were unaffiliated with the school.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In 2025, Swarthmore College said there was a "growing presence of individuals unaffiliated with the College" and campus property had been vandalized.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In October 2025, Syracuse University chancellor Kent Syverud said the protests on campus seemed to have been encouraged by Iran.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] He emphasized that, although there was an initially welcoming atmosphere for both pro-Israel and pro-Palestinian activities, a noticeable shift occurred later.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Syverud expressed his belief that Iran played a significant role in fostering the demonstrations, claiming that there was little to no involvement from the university's own students in the protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Experts raised concern about far-right groups attempting to infiltrate protests to cause harm, and subsequent reactions from militant far-left activists aligned with the anti-fascist movement.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Qatar reportedly contributed $4.7 billion to U.S. academic institutions between 2001 and 2021; Kenneth Marcus of the Brandeis Center suggested this may have affected university administrators' willingness to impose discipline.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Far-right agitators and white nationalists were identified at some protests seeking to sow chaos and violence, and at the UCLA campus occupation, they were among pro-Israeli counter-protesters who attacked the encampment.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A white supremacist affiliated with the Proud Boys was among the counter-protesters supported by far-right activists nationwide.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On October 25, Jonathan Greenblatt of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) and Alyza D.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The website Canary Mission published profiles of students and faculty members it considers antisemitic, and Betar US, a Zionist group, compiled a list of students to be deported.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Several protests were criticized for alleged antisemitism.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some students called some of the incidents reported at protests and on campus "threatening" and said they made them feel unsafe.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Jewish students were targeted for their faith, for wearing Jewish symbols, or were accused of being Zionists and subsequently targeted.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some Jewish students also said the protests created a climate of fear and hate on campus.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to *The Jewish Post*, a survey by Hillel of Jewish students at universities with encampments found that most of them felt unsafe due to encampments.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 72% of respondents wanted them dismantled and 61% considered language used at the protests antisemitic.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Department of Education concluded that University of Michigan and CUNY failed to assess whether the protests made the environment hostile.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Supporters of Israel and some students said that the word "intifada", the phrase "from the river to the sea", and chants comparing Israel and Zionism to Nazism were antisemitic.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Others, including Jewish students, argued against conflating antisemitism with anti-Zionism, and said the charge was used to chill debate.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian and Jewish student protesters said that the protests were not antisemitic.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] *The Guardian* noted that incidents of antisemitism appeared to be "relatively isolated" and likelier to occur when non-students were in a parallel protest.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian student groups at the protests were quick to condemn inflammatory remarks.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some pro-Palestinian Jewish students said they faced antisemitism from pro-Israel activists.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some commentators and politicians, including Mayor Eric Adams, U.S.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Representative Virginia Foxx, and NYPD deputy commissioner of operations Kaz Daughtry, promoted a conspiracy theory that George Soros or some other anonymous figure funded the protest encampments by buying the same brand of tents for many protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In fact, the similar appearance of many encampment tents was due to online retailers' discounts and promotions of particular products.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In fall 2024, chants such as "Divest!" and "Ceasefire now!" reportedly evolved towards more explicitly endorsing Hamas, Hezbollah, and Houthis.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some protesters used slogans such as "Glory to the resistance!", called the October 7 attacks "Al-Aqsa flood", celebrated Yahya Sinwar, and used the Hamas inverted red triangle.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Aidan Herzlinger, vice president of Baruch College's Hillel chapter, said students who attended a Hillel banquet at the college were called "baby killers" and "terrorists".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In November 2024, hundreds of posters depicting faculty members as "wanted" were spread across the University of Rochester campus.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some of the posters accused a Jewish faculty member of ethnic cleansing and contributing to the displacement of Palestinians; others accused a faculty member of racism, hate speech, and intimidation.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] University President Sarah Mangelsdorf called the incident an act of antisemitism.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian protesters and their allies criticized the disposition of many university administrations as perpetuating a "Palestine exception" to academic freedom.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian students and their allies raised concerns about anti-Palestinianism and Islamophobia.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Department of Education were opened at Columbia, Emory University, the University of North Carolina, and at Umass Amherst over their administrations' response to student protests and advocacy since the start of the war.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In May 2024, the New York City Police Department shared images of items it said it had confiscated from a protest at NYU, including "gas masks, ear plugs, helmets, goggles, tape, hammers, knives, ropes, and a book on TERRORISM" that were taken from a student's backpack.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] One pamphlet read, "Death to America!" According to the Anti-Defamation League, on the first anniversary of the October 7 attacks, many of the over 100 protests included chants and other messages "filled with support for terrorist organizations" and symbols such as paragliders.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Demonstrators at Columbia published a statement calling on students "to propagate the successes of the heroic Palestinian armed resistance in weakening Israel and U.S. imperialism and inspiring anti-imperialist struggles around the world".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A study by the Armed Conflict Location and Event Data Project (ACLED) found that 97% of protests were nonviolent and nearly half of those that became violent involved protesters fighting with law enforcement during police interventions.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The guard was out of work for two weeks as a result of injuries.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The students denied using violence, calling their protest peaceful.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students and student journalists also faced violence at the hands of counter-protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] One protester at Columbia was arrested and hospitalized after a counter-protester rammed his car into a group of picketers.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Counter-protesters at the University of Pennsylvania approached the encampment with knives, and in a separate incident sprayed a chemical mixture on protesters' tents, food, and belongings.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 1, 2024, around 10:50 PM, a pro-Israeli group attacked the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) pro-Palestinian protesters' camp for nearly four hours, attempting to breach the barricades surrounding it.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The attackers, reported to have come from outside campus, carried Israeli flags and assaulted students with sticks, stones, poles, metal fencing, and pepper spray.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] They played loud audio of a child crying, threw wood and a metal barrier into the camp, and threw at least six fireworks into the encampment, including one directly at a group of protesters carrying injured people.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A video investigation suggested pro-Palestinian protesters did not initiate any confrontation but acted in defense.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The counter-protesters called for a "Second Nakba", referring to the ethnic cleansing of Palestinians in 1948, and played the Israeli national anthem and Harbu Darbu on loudspeakers during the attack.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to *The Guardian*, counter-protesters included several far-right activists involved in anti-LGBTQ+ and anti-vaccine campaigning.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At Portland State, protesters damaged computers and furniture during their occupation of the campus library.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At Columbia, protesters shattered windows during their occupation of Hamilton Hall.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Police and city workers destroyed students' tents, flags and other encampment supplies while disbanding the encampment at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At George Washington University, protesters defaced a statue of its namesake, President George Washington.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The statue was wrapped with Palestinian scarves and flags, with the words "Genocidal Warmonger University" spray-painted on its base.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students replaced U.S. flags with Palestinian flags on flagpoles at several universities.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In Harvard Yard, student demonstrators affixed three Palestinian flags atop the John Harvard statue on April 27.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The replacement of U.S. flags sparked outrage from some officials, such as New York Mayor Eric Adams.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In response, university administrations and law enforcement agencies intervened to take down the Palestinian flags and reinstate U.S. flags to their original positions.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] With over 3,100 protesters arrested, universities suspended and expelled student protesters, in some cases evicting them from campus housing, and relied on police to forcibly disband occupations.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Most universities that faced encampment protests in the spring attempted to negotiate a disbandment of the encampments, often threatening police sweeps to force an agreement.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many universities initiated disciplinary proceedings against protesters, accusing them of breaking student codes of conduct.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In July 2025, Columbia University disciplined at least 70 students who took part in campus protests with probation, suspensions, degree revocations, and expulsions.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Police departments employed a range of tactics, including dispersing crowds using horses and police in riot gear, deploying pepper balls, using tasers, mass arrests, and tear gas, clearing unauthorized encampments, and beating both students and professors.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Police also assaulted, arrested and restricted access for some journalists while they were covering the protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some Democrats and human rights organizations criticized the police response.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By fall 2024, many universities had strengthened their restrictions on protests, including more than 100 colleges and universities, and several schools had banned camping on their grounds.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Over 200 groups expressed support for the protests, as well as U.S.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Senator Bernie Sanders, various members of Congress, several labor unions, hundreds of university staff in the United Kingdom, and Iran's supreme leader Ali Khamenei.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests were condemned by leaders including President Joe Biden, Prime Minister of the Netherlands Mark Rutte, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, and Australian Prime Minister Anthony Albanese.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] UK Prime Minister Rishi Sunak and Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau raised concerns.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Numerous U.S. corporate leaders announced that they wished to know the protesters' names in order to prevent them from working in their firms.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Among them were Davis Polk & Wardwell, Pershing Square Capital Management, shopping club FabFitFun, health tech startup EasyHealth, Dovehill Capital Management, and restaurant chain Sweetgreen.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A May 2024 divestment referendum at DePaul University returned a 91% vote in favor of divestment.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In April 2024, Columbia College voted on three divestment questions.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The first asked whether Columbia should divest from Israel, the second asked whether it should cancel the Tel Aviv Global Center program, and the third asked whether Columbia should end its dual degree program with Tel Aviv University.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The motions passed by 76%, 68%, and 65%, respectively, with 40% voter participation.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at the University of Pennsylvania voted 73% in favor of disclosing all investments in the school's endowment and 63% in favor of ending the university's relationship with Ghost Robotics, with 22% voter participation.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to a YouGov poll released on May 3, 2024, 47% of Americans opposed the campus protests and 28% supported them.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] American Muslims supported the protests by 75% to 14% while Jewish Americans opposed them by 72% to 18%.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Adults under 45 were more likely to support them than older adults.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 33% believed the response to the protests was not harsh enough, 16% believed it was too harsh, and 20% believed the response was about right.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 48% of Americans over 45 believed the response was not harsh enough, compared to only 16% under 45.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to an Axios poll released on May 7, 2024, 8% of college students participated in the protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 34% blame Hamas, 19% blame Netanyahu, 12% blame the Israeli people, and 12% blame Biden for the destruction in Gaza.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 81% of students supported holding protesters accountable for destroyed property and illegally occupied buildings, 67% considered occupying campus buildings unacceptable, 58% considered refusal to disperse unacceptable, and 90% opposed blocking pro-Israel students.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students were more likely to support the pro-Palestinian encampments, with 45% who supported them strongly or moderately, 30% neutral, and 24% strongly or mildly opposed.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Among those who participated in anti-Israeli protests, 58% said they would not be friends with someone who had marched for Israel, while 64% of students who marched in favor of Israel said they would still be friends with anti-Israeli protesters.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Overall, 40% approved and 42% disapproved of the protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In Canada, 19% of respondents supported the protesters and 48% of respondents opposed the protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] *The New York Times* reported that some scholars considered the protests starkly different from those against the Vietnam War or apartheid South Africa.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to Timothy Naftali, protests against Vietnam in the 1960s did not result in a constituency that felt attacked as an ethnicity, and that the pro-Palestinian demonstrations created "a feeling of insecurity in a much bigger way than the antiwar demonstrations during Vietnam did".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft said current college protests contain "further echoes of the forces that helped give rise to the Nazis", while Columbia University's Chabad chapter said that phrases like "Go back to Poland" and "stop killing children" had been yelled at Jewish students.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In May 2024, some Jewish students on campus said they believed that support for Israel was a "litmus test" leading to their exclusion from campus social life.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In September 2024, after many harassment complaints, the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign banned the ostracism of Jewish students from school clubs for identifying as Zionist.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Far-right influencers and some Republicans portrayed the protests as violent, a "Marxist takeover," and "terrorism".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] *The New York Times* opined that the protests came during a presidential election year in which Democrats had "harnessed promises of stability and normalcy to win critical recent elections" and that the protests were a messaging opportunity for Republicans to divide Democrats.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The newspaper also published an article citing NewsGuard, the Institute for Strategic Dialogue, the Foundation for Defense of Democracies, the Australian Strategic Policy Institute, and Recorded Future on how the media of Russia, China, and Iran had covered the events.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] It concluded that those countries had made overt and covert efforts to capitalize on the protests to denigrate democracy, inflame partisan tensions, criticize Biden ahead of the 2024 presidential election, support Trump, and express support for Hamas and Palestinians generally.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A *Jewish Currents* editor described the movement as providing "cover for the right to expand its attack on protest" in reference to the "draconian" crackdown on protests, saying the "attacks on academic freedom and free speech on campus" were led by right-wingers.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Republicans used antisemitic tropes when denouncing protests as antisemitic, including allusions to conspiracies around George Soros and invoking globalists.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In May 2025, *The New York Times* found that the second Trump administration had called for or implemented over half the proposals of The Heritage Foundation's Project Esther, a conservative program to suppress pro-Palestinian protests and what it classifies as antisemitism.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Initially, *The New York Times* wrote that protests outside the U.S. were "sporadic and smaller, and none [started] a wider student movement".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The "partisan political context" was given as a reason for the intensity of protests in the U.S.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Columbia's status as an Ivy League school, its proximity to New York City and national news media, and its large population of Jewish students were described as fueling increased media attention and political scrutiny that helped spread the protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to a *Washington Monthly* study in May, pro-Palestinian demonstrations and encampments were more prevalent at elite U.S. universities.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 3, NPR described the protests abroad as "a growing global student movement", with student protests in the United Kingdom focused on "an increasingly high-profile nationwide campaign to end British arms exports to Israel".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to NBC News, the protests abroad inspired by protests in the U.S. did not have the intensity of U.S. protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 7, protests had escalated in Europe after mass arrests at the University of Amsterdam, with occupations of campus buildings in Germany, France, and Belgium, and encampments on several European campuses.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The Associated Press described protests at Sciences Po in Paris as "echoing similar encampments and solidarity demonstrations across the United States".
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 9, protests were widespread at universities in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka, while smaller ones were held at Japanese and South Korean universities.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Media coverage of the protests was criticized as sensationalized and failing to focus on the protesters' demands and grievances.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Dana Bash was criticized for likening college protests to the rise of antisemitism in the 1930s in Europe.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The lack of student protesters' voices in most national media coverage was also criticized.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Student reporters, in particular, were praised for their work covering the protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The global wave of student- and staff-led demonstrations on university campuses continued in 2025, with protests at hundreds of campuses in North America, Europe, Australia, Africa, and Asia.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Inspired by the anti-apartheid and Vietnam War campus protests, students and faculty called for divestment, academic boycott, and institutional transparency about ties to Israel and military contractors.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The movement intensified in 2025 after Israel's offensive in Rafah and renewed violence in Gaza, as well as solidarity actions in response to police crackdowns on US campuses.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the United States, at Columbia University, there were renewed encampments and building occupations, including the occupation of Butler Library ("Basel Al-Araj Popular University").
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] There were mass arrests by the NYPD and over 100 students were suspended or barred from campus.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In July 2025, Columbia disciplined at least 70 students who took part in campus protests, with punishments including probation, suspensions, degree revocations, and expulsions.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] At the University of Washington, protesters occupied an engineering building, demanding an end to ties with Boeing over its military contracts.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] More than 30 protesters were arrested after police intervention.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Thirty-four people were arrested inside the School of Engineering building and over $1 million in damage was done to the structure.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Canada, after a three-day student protest that included blockades and vandalism, the Quebec Superior Court issued a 10-day injunction barring pro-Palestinian protesters at McGill University from obstructing campus access or disrupting academic activities.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Citing threats to safety and academic continuity, McGill sought legal intervention amid calls for divestment from companies linked to Israel.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] It has also initiated steps to sever ties with the undergraduate student union over its alleged failure to distance itself from disruptive activism.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Germany, Berlin police cleared a protest in April 2025 at Humboldt University, where 89 pro-Palestinian demonstrators had occupied a lecture hall to oppose the planned deportation of four international students accused of participating in violent protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The police launched around 100 criminal investigations related to the occupation, citing vandalism, use of incendiary objects, and alleged extremist symbols.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The university justified police intervention partly due to banners denying Israel's right to exist, an issue sensitive in Germany due to its post-Holocaust commitment to supporting Israel.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Germany is facing criticism for issuing orders to deport four pro-Palestinian activists who have been convicted of no crimes.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the Netherlands there were occupations and encampments at the University of Amsterdam, Utrecht University, Radboud University, and others.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Several protests were met with police intervention, with students sustaining injuries.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the United Kingdom, members of Oxford Action for Palestine occupied the Radcliffe Camera, protesting the alleged complicity of the University of Oxford in Israeli military actions in Gaza and the West Bank and accusing the institution of cutting off dialogue.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The university condemned the disruption, citing safety concerns, and said it was working to remove the protesters, who had renamed the library after a Palestinian political figure linked to a group several Western governments have designated a terrorist organization.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] At the University of Glasgow, students from the Justice for Palestine Society disrupted campus events in April, calling for divestment from arms companies accused of complicity in what they describe as genocide in Gaza.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Across the UK, over 100 students and staff have faced disciplinary action, with some universities reportedly working with private intelligence firms to monitor protests.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Many universities called on police to clear encampments and occupations, resulting in mass arrests and suspensions of students and faculty.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Some institutions agreed to partial demands, including publishing lists of ties to Israeli entities or freezing select partnerships.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The US government threatened funding cuts to universities that did not address alleged antisemitism or campus unrest, and some protesters faced deportation proceedings.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Civil liberties groups and faculty organizations expressed concern over free speech, academic freedom, and the militarization of campus policing.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In July 2025, Columbia University disciplined at least 70 students who took part in campus protests, with punishments including probation, suspensions, degree revocations, and expulsions.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Canada, after pro-Palestinian protests at the University of Toronto and a more than 60-day encampment on its St.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] George campus, the University of Toronto Faculty Association (UTFA) voted to divest from Israel, citing its opposition to what it called Israel's "illegal occupation" of Palestinian territories.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The motion, which passed with 52% support, urges the Ontario University Pension Plan to swiftly divest from entities linked to the occupation or arms production potentially used by Israel in Palestine, aligning the move with the university’s existing divestment policy on Russia.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the Netherlands, the University of Amsterdam, Tilburg University, Utrecht University, Erasmus University Rotterdam, and Radboud University have cut ties with nine Israeli institutes, with some also suspending future collaborations.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the UK, King’s College Cambridge announced divestment from arms and companies involved in the Israeli occupation.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Ireland, Trinity College Dublin severed all ties with Israeli universities and companies, becoming the first Irish university to fully divest.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] This includes ending investments, commercial relations, academic collaborations, and Erasmus+ exchanges.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The move follows a taskforce review and a five-day student encampment protesting the college's ties to Israel.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The university had investments in 13 Israeli companies, some linked to illegal settlements.
[src:university-college-london/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The decision was praised by student leaders and politicians, who called it a model for other institutions to follow.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] This is a complete **list of acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for the year 1905**.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] Note that the first parliament of the United Kingdom was held in 1801; parliaments between 1707 and 1800 were either parliaments of Great Britain or of Ireland).
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] For acts passed up until 1707, see the list of acts of the Parliament of England and the list of acts of the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] For acts passed from 1707 to 1800, see the list of acts of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] See also the list of acts of the Parliament of Ireland.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] For acts of the devolved parliaments and assemblies in the United Kingdom, see the list of acts of the Scottish Parliament, the list of acts of the Northern Ireland Assembly, and the list of acts and measures of Senedd Cymru; see also the list of acts of the Parliament of Northern Ireland.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] The number shown after each act's title is its chapter number.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] Acts passed before 1963 are cited using this number, preceded by the year(s) of the reign during which the relevant parliamentary session was held; thus the Union with Ireland Act 1800 is cited as "39 & 40 Geo.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] 67", meaning the 67th act passed during the session that started in the 39th year of the reign of George III and which finished in the 40th year of that reign.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] Note that the modern convention is to use Arabic numerals in citations (thus "41 Geo.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] Acts of the last session of the Parliament of Great Britain and the first session of the Parliament of the United Kingdom are both cited as "41 Geo.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] Acts passed from 1963 onwards are simply cited by calendar year and chapter number.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] The sixth session of the 27th Parliament of the United Kingdom, which met from 14 February 1905 until 11 August 1905.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p01] This session was also traditionally cited as **5 Ed.
