[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p03] Electric Lighting (Scotland) Act 1890 (53 & 54 Vict. c.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p03] Electric Lighting (Scotland) Act 1902 (2 Edw.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p03] Burgh Police (Scotland) Act 1892 (55 & 56 Vict. c.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p03] Housing of the Working Classes Act 1890 (53 & 54 Vict. c.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p03] General Pier and Harbour Act 1861 (24 & 25 Vict. c.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p03] South Lancashire Tramways Act 1901 (1 Edw.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p03] London Government Act 1899 (62 & 63 Vict. c.
[src:university-college-london/5-edw-7-p03] Ulster and Connaught Light Railways Act 1903 (3 Edw.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] The Italianate building was designed by Sir James Pennethorne between 1867 and 1870 as headquarters for the University of London.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] It occupied the northernmost section of the former garden of Burlington House.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] It was a grand building, but not especially large.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] The University of London is a federal university and this early central building contained little besides examination halls and a few offices; the premises of several of the constituent colleges were larger.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] The university vacated Burlington Gardens in 1900 for the Imperial Institute building in South Kensington.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] Briefly the headquarters of the National Antarctic Expedition, in 1902 it was given to the Civil Service Commission.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] During World War 2 the building was used to hear the appeals of high level British Fascists such as Barry Domvile against their continued internment.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] One of Domvile's appeals was heard here on 15th April, 1942.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] In 1970, this was the site of the Department of Ethnography of the British Museum, which housed its collections from the Americas, Africa, the Pacific and Australia, as well as tribal Asia and Europe, because of lack of space in the museum's main building in Bloomsbury.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] Between 1970 and 1997, the building, as the Museum of Mankind, hosted around 75 exhibitions, including many famous ones such as *Nomad and City*, 1976, and *Living Arctic*, 1987.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] It was created by Keeper of Ethnography Adrian Digby in the 1960s, and opened by his successor William Fagg.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] Fagg was succeeded by Malcolm Mcleod in 1974, and by John Mack in 1990.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] The museum ceased exhibiting at Burlington Gardens in 1997 and the Department of Ethnography moved back to the British Museum in Bloomsbury in 2004.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] After the ethnography collection's return to Bloomsbury the building was purchased by the Royal Academy.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] In 1998 an architectural competition was held to connect it with Burlington House, which was won by Michael Hopkins & Partners.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] This was abandoned as the Heritage Lottery Fund was not persuaded that there was sufficient need for the project, which would have cost £80 million.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] In about 2005 the building was brought back into use by the Royal Academy, the tenant of the original wing of Burlington House and the wing which lies between the two buildings.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] It was used mainly by the Royal Academy Schools.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] On 29 August 2006, the building was damaged by a fire, but there was no loss of academy artworks as it was being prepared for a future exhibition.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] In 2006 Colin St John Wilson drew up a masterplan for the whole complex, which included a more modest link between the buildings than that proposed by Hopkins.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] However, Wilson died the following year, which led to another competition being held in 2008, won by David Chipperfield Architects.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] In order to raise capital for Chipperfield's design, the building was lent to the commercial gallery Haunch of Venison, which occupied the site from 2009 to 2011 while their existing building was being renovated.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] In 2012 space in the building was lent to the Pace Gallery, which occupies it on a 15-year lease.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] A second application to the HLF, for £12.7m to go towards a £36 million project, was successful in 2013.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] This included a sculpture court in the bridge between the buildings, a lecture hall where that of the University of London originally stood and a permanent home for Giampietrino’s full-size copy of Leonardo da Vinci’s *Last Supper*.
[src:university-college-london/6-burlington-gardens] The redevelopment was completed in 2018, in time for the academy's 250th anniversary that year.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In 1896, Housman published *A Shropshire Lad*, a cycle of poems marked by the author's pessimism and preoccupation with early death, which gradually acquired a wide readership and appealed particularly to a younger audience during World War I.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Another collection, entitled *Last Poems*, appeared in 1922.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman's poetry became popular for musical settings.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Following his death, further poems from his notebooks were published by his brother Laurence, titled *More Poems* (1936).
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman's *A Shropshire Lad* includes some iconic individual poems like "Loveliest of trees, the cherry now" (II), "When I was one-and-twenty" (XIII), "Is my team ploughing" (XXVII) and "Into my heart an air that kills" (XL).
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] His mother died on his twelfth birthday, and his father, a country solicitor, then married an elder cousin, Lucy, in 1873.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Two of his siblings became prominent writers, sister Clemence Housman and brother Laurence Housman.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman was educated at King Edward's School in Birmingham and later Bromsgrove School, where he revealed his academic promise and won prizes for his poems.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In 1877, he won an open scholarship to St John's College, Oxford, and went there to study classics.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Although introverted by nature, Housman formed strong friendships with two roommates, Moses John Jackson (1858–1923) and A.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Though Housman obtained a first in classical Moderations in 1879, his dedication to textual analysis led him to neglect the ancient history and philosophy that formed part of the Greats curriculum.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Accordingly, he failed the Finals and had to return humiliated in Michaelmas term to resit the exam so as to at least gain a lower-level pass degree.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Though some attribute Housman's unexpected performance in his exams directly to his unrequited feelings for Jackson, most biographers adduce more obvious causes.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman was indifferent to philosophy and overconfident in his exceptional gifts and he spent too much time with his friends.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He may also have been distracted by news of his father's desperate illness.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] After Oxford, Jackson went to work as a clerk in the Patent Office in London and he also arranged a job there for Housman.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The two shared a flat at 82 Talbot Road, Bayswater, with Jackson's brother Adalbert until 1885, when Housman moved to lodgings of his own, probably after Jackson responded to a declaration of love by telling Housman that he could not reciprocate his feelings.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Two years later, Jackson moved to India, placing more distance between himself and Housman.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] When he returned briefly to England in 1889 to marry, Housman was not invited to the wedding and knew nothing about it until the couple had left the country.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Adalbert Jackson died in 1892 and Housman commemorated him in a poem published as "XLII – A.J.J." of *More Poems* (1936).
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Meanwhile, Housman pursued his classical studies independently, and published scholarly articles on Horace, Propertius, Ovid, Aeschylus, Euripides and Sophocles.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He also completed an edition of Propertius, which however was rejected by both Oxford University Press and Macmillan in 1885, and was destroyed after his death.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He gradually acquired such a high reputation that in 1892 he was offered and accepted the professorship of Latin at University College London (UCL).
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] When, during his tenure, an immensely rare Coverdale Bible of 1535 was discovered in the UCL library and presented to the Library Committee, Housman (who had become an atheist while at Oxford) remarked that it would be better to sell it to "buy some really useful books with the proceeds".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Although Housman's early work and his responsibilities as a professor included both Latin and Greek, he began to specialise in Latin poetry.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] When asked later why he had stopped writing about Greek verse, he responded, "I found that I could not attain to excellence in both." In 1911 he took the Kennedy Professorship of Latin at Trinity College, Cambridge, where he remained for the rest of his life.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Between 1903 and 1930, Housman published his critical edition of Manilius's *Astronomicon* in five volumes.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He also edited Juvenal (1905) and Lucan (1926).
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He was and may remain the last great textual critic".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In the eyes of Harry Eyres, however, Housman was "famously dry" as a professor, and his influence led to a scholarly style in the study of literature and poetry that was philological and without emotion.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Many colleagues were unnerved by Housman's scathing attacks on those he thought guilty of shoddy scholarship.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In his paper "The Application of Thought to Textual Criticism" (1921) he wrote: "A textual critic engaged upon his business is not at all like Newton investigating the motion of the planets: he is much more like a dog hunting for fleas".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He declared many of his contemporary scholars to be stupid, lazy, vain, or all three, saying: "Knowledge is good, method is good, but one thing beyond all others is necessary; and that is to have a head, not a pumpkin, on your shoulders, and brains, not pudding, in your head".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Gow, quoted examples of these attacks, noting that they "were often savage in the extreme".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Gow also related how Housman intimidated students, sometimes reducing the women to tears.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] According to Gow, Housman could never remember the names of female students, maintaining that "had he burdened his memory by the distinction between Miss Jones and Miss Robinson, he might have forgotten that between the second and fourth declension".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Among the more notable students at his Cambridge lectures was Enoch Powell, one of whose own Classical emendations was later complimented by Housman.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In his private life, Housman enjoyed country walks, gastronomy, air travel and making frequent visits to France, where he read "books which were banned in Britain as pornographic" but he struck A.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Benson, a fellow don, as being "descended from a long line of maiden aunts".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] His feelings about his poetry were ambivalent and he certainly treated it as secondary to his scholarship.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He did not speak in public about his poems until 1933, when he gave a lecture "The Name and Nature of Poetry", arguing there that poetry should appeal to emotions rather than to the intellect.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] His ashes are buried just outside St Laurence's Church, Ludlow.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] A cherry tree was planted there in his memory (see *A Shropshire Lad* II) and replaced by the Housman Society in 2003 with a new cherry tree nearby.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In the same vein, Harry Eyres interpreted it as "what you could see as an act of self-punishment" that so many years were devoted to "a minor Roman versifier whose long didactic poem on astrology must rank as one of the most obscure in the entire annals of poetry".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] During his years in London, Housman completed *A Shropshire Lad*, a cycle of 63 poems.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] After one publisher had turned it down, he helped subsidise its publication in 1896.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] At first selling slowly, it rapidly became a lasting success.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Its appeal to English musicians had helped to make it widely known before World War I, when its themes struck a powerful chord with English readers.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The book has been in print continuously since May 1896.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The poems are marked by pessimism and preoccupation with death, without religious consolation (Housman had become an atheist while still an undergraduate).
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman wrote many of them while living in Highgate, London, before ever visiting Shropshire, which he presented in an idealised pastoral light as his 'land of lost content'.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman himself acknowledged that "No doubt I have been unconsciously influenced by the Greeks and Latins, but [the] chief sources of which I am conscious are Shakespeare's songs, the Scottish Border ballads, and Heine".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman began collecting a new set of poems after the First World War.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] His early work was an influence on many British poets who became famous by their writing about the war, and he wrote several poems as occasional verse to commemorate the war dead.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] This included his *Epitaph on an Army of Mercenaries*, honouring the British Expeditionary Force, an elite but small force of professional soldiers sent to Belgium at the start of the war.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In the early 1920s, when Moses Jackson was dying in Canada, Housman wanted to assemble his best unpublished poems so that Jackson could read them before his death.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] These later poems, mostly written before 1910, show a greater variety of subject and form than those in *A Shropshire Lad* but lack its consistency.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He published his new collection as *Last Poems* (1922), feeling that his inspiration was exhausted and that he should not publish more in his lifetime.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] After Housman's death in 1936, his brother, Laurence published further poems in *More Poems* (1936), *A.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] E .H.: Some Poems, Some Letters and a Personal Memoir by his Brother* (1937), and *Collected Poems* (1939).
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] H.* includes humorous verse such as a parody of Longfellow's poem *Excelsior*.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman also wrote a parodic *Fragment of a Greek Tragedy*, in English, first published in 1883 in *The Bromsgrovian*, the magazine of his old school, and frequently reprinted.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Sparrow himself adds, "How difficult it is to achieve a satisfactory analysis may be judged by considering the last poem in *A Shropshire Lad*.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Of its four stanzas, Housman tells us that two were 'given' him ready made; one was coaxed forth from his subconsciousness an hour or two later; the remaining one took months of conscious composition.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In 1942, Laurence Housman also deposited an essay entitled "A.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman's 'De Amicitia'" in the British Library, with the proviso that it was not to be published for 25 years.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman's homosexuality and his love for Moses Jackson.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Despite the conservative nature of the times and his own caution in public life, Housman was quite open in his poetry, and especially in *A Shropshire Lad*, about his deeper sympathies.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Poem XXX of that sequence, for instance, speaks of how "Fear contended with desire": "Others, I am not the first, / Have willed more mischief than they durst".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] His poem "Oh who is that young sinner with the handcuffs on his wrists?", written after the trial of Oscar Wilde, addressed more general attitudes towards homosexuals.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] This refers to an old paraphrasing for homosexuality in English law.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman's poetry, especially *A Shropshire Lad*, was set to music by many British, and in particular English, composers in the first half of the 20th century.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The national, pastoral and traditional elements of his style resonated with similar trends in English music.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In 1904, the cycle *A Shropshire Lad* was set by Arthur Somervell, who in 1898 had begun to develop the concept of the English song-cycle in his version of Tennyson's "Maud".
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Stephen Banfield believes it was acquaintance with Somervell's cycle that led other composers to set Housman: Ralph Vaughan Williams is likely to have attended the first performance at the Aeolian Hall on 3 February 1905.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] His well-known cycle of six songs *On Wenlock Edge*, for string quartet, tenor and piano, was published in 1909.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Between 1909 and 1911, George Butterworth produced settings in two collections, *Six Songs from A Shropshire Lad* and *Bredon Hill and Other Songs*.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He also wrote the orchestral tone poem *A Shropshire Lad*, first performed at Leeds Festival in 1912.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Ivor Gurney was another composer who made renowned settings of Housman's poems.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Towards the end of World War I, he was working on his cycle *Ludlow and Teme*, for voice and string quartet (published in 1919), and went on to compose the eight-song cycle *The Western Playland* in 1921.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] One more who set Housman songs during this period was John Ireland in the song cycle, *The Land of Lost Content* (1920–21).
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Charles Wilfred Orr produced 24 Housman settings in songs and song cycles composed from the 1920s into the 1950s.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Even composers not directly associated with the 'pastoral' tradition, such as Arnold Bax, Lennox Berkeley and Arthur Bliss, were attracted to Housman's poetry.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Housman's attitude to musical interpretations of his poetry, and indeed to music in general, was either indifference or torment.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] He told his friend Percy Withers that he knew nothing of music and it meant nothing to him.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Withers once played him a record of the Vaughan Williams setting, but realised he had made a mistake when he saw the look of disgust on the poet's face.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Nevertheless, by 1976, a catalogue listed 400 musical settings of Housman's poems.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] As of 2024, Lieder Net Archive records 678 settings of 188 texts.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The earliest commemoration of Housman was in the chapel of Trinity College in Cambridge, where there is a memorial brass on the south wall.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The Latin inscription was composed by his colleague there, A.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Gow, who was also the author of a biographical and bibliographical sketch published immediately following his death.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] From 1947, University College London's academic common room was dedicated to his memory as the Housman Room.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Blue plaques followed later elsewhere, the first being on Byron Cottage in Highgate in 1969, recording the fact that *A Shropshire Lad* was written there.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] More followed, placed on his Worcestershire birthplace, his homes and school in Bromsgrove.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The latter were encouraged by the Housman Society, which was founded in the town in 1973.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Another initiative was the statue in Bromsgrove High Street, showing the poet striding with walking stick in hand.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The work of local sculptor Kenneth Potts, it was unveiled on 22 March 1985.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The blue plaques in Worcestershire were set up on the centenary of *A Shropshire Lad* in 1996.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] In September of the same year, a memorial window lozenge was dedicated at Poets' Corner in Westminster Abbey.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The following year saw the première of Tom Stoppard's play *The Invention of Love*, whose subject is the relationship between Housman and Moses Jackson.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] As the 150th anniversary of his birth approached, London University inaugurated its Housman lectures on classical subjects in 2005, initially given every second year then annually after 2011.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] The anniversary itself in 2009 saw the publication of a new edition of *A Shropshire Lad*, including pictures from across Shropshire taken by local photographer Gareth Thomas.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] Among other events, there were performances of Vaughan Williams's *On Wenlock Edge* and Ivor Gurney's *Ludlow and Teme* at St Laurence's Church in Ludlow.
[src:university-college-london/a-e-housman] These lectures are listed by date of delivery, with date of first publication given separately if different.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The **A-level** (**Advanced Level**) is a main school leaving qualification of the General Certificate of Education in England, Wales, Northern Ireland, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It is available as an alternative qualification in other countries, where it is similarly known as an A-Level.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Students generally study for A-levels over a two-year period.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] For much of their history, A-levels have been examined by written exams taken at the end of these two years.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2015, Ofqual decided to change back to a terminal approach where students sit all examinations at the end of the second year.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] AS is still offered, but as a separate qualification; AS grades no longer count towards a subsequent A-level in England.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Most students study three or four A-level subjects simultaneously during the two post-16 years (ages 16–18) in a secondary school, in a sixth form college, in a further and higher education college, or in a tertiary college, as part of their further education.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In the UK, some schools and colleges offer one-year A Level retake programmes for students who wish to improve their grades.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels were introduced in 1951 as a standardised school-leaving qualification, replacing the Higher School Certificate.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The examinations were taken on a subject-by-subject basis, the subjects being chosen according to the strengths and interests of the student.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] This encouraged specialization and in-depth study of three to four subjects.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] At first, A-levels were graded as simply distinction, pass or fail (although students were given an indication of their marks, to the nearest 5%).
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Candidates obtaining a distinction originally had the option to sit a scholarship level paper on the same material, to attempt to win one of 400 national scholarships.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The scholarship level was renamed the S-Level in 1963.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Quite soon, rising numbers of students taking the A-level examinations required more differentiation of achievement below the S-Level standard.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Grades were therefore introduced, with recommendations by the Secondary School Examinations Council (SSEC) of approximate proportions of pupils for each grade.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The O grade was equivalent to a GCE Ordinary Level pass which indicated a performance equivalent to the lowest pass grade at Ordinary Level.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Over time, the validity of this system was questioned because, rather than reflecting a standard, norm referencing simply maintained a specific proportion of candidates at each grade, which in small cohorts was subject to statistical fluctuations in standards.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In 1984, the government's Secondary Examinations Council decided to replace the norm referencing with criterion referencing: grades would in future be awarded on examiner judgement thus eliminating a possible inadequacy of the existing scheme.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The criterion referencing scheme came into effect for the summer 1987 exams as the system set examiners specific criteria for the awarding of B and E grades to candidates, and then divided out the other grades according to fixed percentages.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Rather than awarding an Ordinary Level for the lowest pass, a new "N" (for Nearly passed) was introduced.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Criticisms of A-level grading continued, and when Curriculum 2000 was introduced, the decision was made to have specific criteria for each grade, and the 'N' grade was abolished.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In 1989, Advanced Supplementary (AS) awards were introduced; they were intended to broaden the subjects a pupil studied post 16, and were to complement rather than be part of a pupil's A-level studies.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] AS-Levels were generally taken over two years, and in a subject the pupil was not studying at A-Level.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Each AS level contained half the content of an A-Level, and at the same level of difficulty.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Initially, a student might study three subjects at A-Level and one at AS-Level, or often even four subjects at A-Level.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] However, due to decreasing public spending on education over time, a growing number of schools and sixth form colleges would now arrange for their pupils to study for three A-Levels instead of four.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels evolved gradually from a two-year linear course with an exam at the end, to a modular course, between the late 1980s and 2000.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] By the year 2000 there was a strong educational reason to standardise the exam and offer greater breadth to students through modules and there was also a pragmatic case based on the inefficiency of linear courses where up to 30% of students were failing to complete or pass.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Curriculum 2000 was introduced in September 2000, with the first new examinations taken in January and June of the following year.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The Curriculum 2000 reforms also replaced the S-Level extension paper with the Advanced Extension Award.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The Conservative Party under Prime Minister David Cameron initiated reforms for A-levels to change from modular to the current linear structure.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] British Examination Boards (Edexcel, AQA and OCR) regulated and accredited by the government of the United Kingdom responded to the government's reform announcements by modifying specifications of several A-level subjects.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] On 18 March 2020, A-level examinations were cancelled in order to curtail the spread of COVID-19 in the 2019–2020 coronavirus pandemic.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The A-level and AS-level qualifications would instead be awarded based upon a mix of teacher assessment and informal "mock" exams taken earlier in the school year.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] On 6 January 2021, Secretary of State for Education Gavin Williamson confirmed that the 2020/21 series of A-levels would also be cancelled, pending further arrangements by Ofqual and the Department for Education.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Prior to the 2015 government reforms of the A-level system, A-levels had (since the Curriculum 2000 reforms) consisted of two equally weighted parts: AS (Advanced Subsidiary) Level, usually assessed in the first year of study, and "A2 Level", usually assessed in the second year of study.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It was typical for an AS course to comprise two or three modules, with the A2 half of the course comprising two or three modules, for a total of four or six modules.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The modules within each part may have been equally weighted, or be of varying weights.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Modules were either assessed by externally marked papers, or by school-assessed, externally moderated coursework.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Following the reforms, A-Levels and AS-Levels have been decoupled, with AS-Level results no longer counting towards the A-Level qualification.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The AS-Level consists of the first half of the A-Level course, and can be taught alongside the first year of the full A-Level course.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Grades are determined by adding up the mark for each component (which is sometimes weighted) and applying a grade boundary.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A wide variety of subjects are offered at A-level by the five exam boards.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Although exam boards often alter their curricula, this table shows the majority of subjects which are consistently available for study.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The number of A-level exams taken by students can vary.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A typical route is to study four subjects at AS level and then drop down to three at A2 level, although some students continue with their fourth subject.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Three is usually the minimum number of A-levels required for university entrance, with some universities specifying the need for a fourth AS subject.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] There is no limit set on the number of A-levels one can study, and a number of students take five or more A-levels.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It is permissible to take A-levels in languages one already speaks fluently, or courses with overlapping content, even if not always fully recognized by universities.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] There are many options that are in place for students to choose to do coursework.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Those who do not reach the minimum standard required for a grade E receive the non-grade **U** (ungraded/unclassified), and those who fail to complete any of the subject's components will receive an **X**.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The process to decide these grades for modular A-levels involves the uniform mark scheme (UMS).
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Under this scheme, four-module A-levels have a maximum mark of 400 UMS (or 200 UMS each for AS and A2), and six-module A-levels have a maximum mark of 600 (or 300 UMS each for AS and A2).
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The maximum UMS within AS and A2 may be split unequally between each modules.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] For example, a Physics AS may have two exam modules worth 90 UMS and 150 UMS, and a coursework module worth 60 UMS.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The 'raw marks' i.e. actual score received on a test may differ from UMS awarded.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] On each assignment, the correspondence of raw marks to UMS is decided by setting grade boundaries, a process which involves consultation by subject experts and consideration of statistics, aiming to keep standards for each grade the same year on year.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Achieving less than 40% results in a U (unclassified).
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] For passing grades, 40% corresponds to an E grade, 50% a D, 60% a C, 70% a B, and 80% an A.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The A* grade was introduced in 2010 and is awarded to candidates who average 80% UMS across all modules, with a score over 90% UMS in all A2 modules.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In Mathematics, which comprises six 100 UMS modules, only the C3 and C4 modules count towards this requirement.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In Further Mathematics and Additional Further Mathematics, where more than three A2 modules can be taken, the three best-scoring A2 modules count.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Recent research and the corresponding findings have shown that over a time span of several years students from Northern Ireland outperformed students from England and Wales in A-level examinations.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] According to UCAS and HKEAA, the Hong Kong A-level examination has historically been benchmarked against the UK A-levels.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In general, a UK A grade is broadly equivalent to a Hong Kong A-C grade.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] This conclusion is based mainly on the percentage of pupils achieving the respective grades in respective exams.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In the UK, on average 25% of participants of each subject achieved an A grade every year, compared to the 25% A-C rate in Hong Kong – A(4%), A-B (10%), A-C (25%).
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] According to the BBC, the percentage of students achieving an A* is about 8–10%, which essentially lies within the A-B range of their Hong Kong counterparts in respective subjects.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In the United States of America the high school diploma is the qualification generally required for entry into colleges and universities.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Students are usually evaluated and granted admission to US higher education institutions based on a combination of school marks, via a transcript from their high school, and a college entrance exam, most commonly the SAT or ACT.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In the United Kingdom, the high school diploma is considered to be at the level of the General Certificate of Secondary Education (GCSE), which is awarded at Year 11.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] For college and university admissions, the high school diploma may be accepted in lieu of the GCSE if an average grade of C is obtained in subjects with a GCSE counterpart.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] As the more academically rigorous A-levels awarded at Year 13 are expected for university admission, the high school diploma alone is generally not considered to meet university requirements.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] College Entrance Examination Board (CEEB) tests, such as the SAT, SAT Subject Tests, or the ACT, may also be considered.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service (UCAS) recommends that in addition to a high school diploma, grades of 3 or above in at least two, or ideally three, Advanced Placement exams may be considered as meeting general entry requirements for admission.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Access arrangements must be approved by the exam board concerned.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] There are others available, but these are the most commonly used.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A-level examinations in the UK are currently administered through 5 examination boards: AQA, OCR, Edexcel (London Examinations), WJEC/Eduqas and CCEA.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The present 5 can trace their roots via a series of mergers or acquisitions to one or more of the originally 9 GCE Examination boards.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Additionally, there are four examination boards offering A-level qualifications internationally: OxfordAQA, Edexcel, Learning Resource Network (LRN) and the CIE.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] OCR and CIE are both branches of the parent organisation, Cambridge Assessment.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] OxfordAQA is a partnership between AQA and Oxford University Press.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In the UK it is customary for schools to register with multiple examination boards and to "mix and match" A-levels to get a combined curriculum that fits the school profile.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The exam boards finance themselves through the fees charged to the schools for administering the examination.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In addition to the centre registration fee, A-level Mathematics will raise £120.00 per student, while Biology, Physics and Chemistry £90.00 per subject and languages such as Spanish, French and German £100.00 or £201.15 depending on the syllabus.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels are usually studied by students in Sixth Form, which refers to the last two years of secondary education in England, Wales and Northern Ireland, taken at ages 16–18.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Some secondary schools have their own Sixth Form, which admits students from lower year groups, but will often accept external applications.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] There are also many specialist Sixth Form and Further Education Colleges which admit from feeder schools across a large geographic area.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Admission to A-level programmes is at the discretion of providers, and usually depends on GCSE grades.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A typical requirement would be 5 A*-C grades at GCSE, although requirements can be higher, particularly for independent schools and grammar schools.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels are offered as an alternate qualification by a small number of educational institutions in Scotland, in place of the standard Scottish Higher, and the Advanced Higher levels of the Scottish Qualifications Certificate.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The schools that offer A-levels are mainly private fee-paying schools particularly for students wishing to attend university in England.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Many international schools choose to use the British system for their wide recognition.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Furthermore, students may choose to sit the papers of British examination bodies at education centres around the world, such as those belonging to the British Council.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] According to the British Council, A-levels are similar to the American Advanced Placement courses which are themselves equivalent to first-year courses of America's four-year bachelor's degrees.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A-level students often apply to universities before they have taken their final exams, with applications administered centrally through UCAS.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] British universities (including Scottish universities, which receive many applicants taking A-levels) consider GCSEs, AS-level results, predicted A-level results, and extracurricular accomplishments when deciding whether applicants should be made an offer through UCAS.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] These offers may be 'unconditional', guaranteeing a place regardless of performance in A2 examinations.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Far more often, the offers are conditional on A-level grades, and become void should the student fail to achieve the marks expected by the university (for example, conditional offer of three A-levels at grades B-B-C).
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Universities may specify which subjects they wish these grades to be in (for example, conditional offer of grades A-A-B with a grade A in Mathematics).
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The offer may include additional requirements, such as attaining a particular grade in the Sixth Term Examination Paper.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The university is obliged to accept the candidate if the conditions are met, but is not obliged to reject a candidate who misses the requirements.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Leniency may in particular be shown if the candidate narrowly misses grades.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A-level grades are also sometimes converted into numerical scores, typically UCAS tariff scores.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Under the new UCAS system starting in 2017, an A* grade at A-level is worth 56 points, while an A is worth 48, a B is worth 40, a C is worth 32, a D is 24, and a E is worth 16; so a university may instead demand that an applicant achieve 112 points, instead of the equivalent offer of B-B-C.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] This allows greater flexibility to students, as 112 points could also, for example, be achieved through the combination A-B-D, which would not have met the requirements of a B-B-C offer because of the D grade.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Depending on the specific offer made, a combination of more than 3 subjects (typically 4 or 5) with lower grades, or points from non-academic input such as higher level music grades or a Key Skills course, may also be accepted by the university.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The text of the offer determines whether this flexibility is available – "112 UCAS Points" likely would, while "112 UCAS Points from three A-level subjects" would not.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] There are currently three examination boards which provide an international variant of the United Kingdom A-level examinations to international students.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] These are Cambridge International Examinations (CIE), Edexcel and OxfordAQA.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] 2020-21 due to COVID-19 grades were teacher awarded, rather than examined.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The most common criticism of the A-level system is an accusation of grade inflation.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The press have noted the steady rise in average grades for several consecutive years and drawn the conclusion that A-levels are becoming consistently easier.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A 2007 report by Robert Coe compared students' scores in the ALIS ability test with equivalent grades achieved in A-level exams over a period of approximately 20 years; he found that students of similar ability were achieving on average about 2 grades higher than in the past.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In the case of maths it was nearer to 3.5 grades higher.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The government and teaching bodies maintain that the improved grades represent higher levels of achievement due to improved and more experienced teaching methods, but some educationalists and journalists argue that the change is due to grade inflation and the examinations getting easier.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It has also been suggested that government pressure on schools to achieve high examination results has led them to coach students to pass the examination rather than understand the subject.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2000, the A-level system was changed to examine students at the end of each of the two years of A-level study, rather than only at the end of the two years.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The results of the first year's exam (AS-level) allowed students to drop subjects they find difficult after one year and to retake AS examinations to achieve a higher grade at that level.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The availability to resit the AS paper, with the best mark contributing to the full A level, has improved results of the A level.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Some believe that students are tending to select easier subjects in order to achieve higher grades.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Universities in Britain have complained that the increasing number of A grades awarded makes it hard to distinguish between students at the upper end of the ability spectrum.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Many universities administer their own entrance tests such as the BMAT and LNAT for specific courses, or conduct interviews to select applicants.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2005, the head of admissions at the University of Cambridge outlined changes he believed should be made to the current system, particularly the use of the Advanced Extension Awards, a more challenging qualification based on the more advanced content of the A-level syllabus.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] More universities have wanted to see applicants' individual module results to see how comfortably they have achieved their result due to fears that the A-level might not offer an accurate test of ability, or that it is a good prediction of future academic success.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2002, allegations that students had been given lower marks than they deserved in order to fix overall results and make the pass rate seem lower than it had been in previous years were raised.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The Tomlinson Inquiry was set up to ascertain whether this was an underhand way to disprove that A-levels were becoming too easy.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] As a result, some papers were re-marked but only 1,220 A-level and 733 AS-level students saw an improvement to their results.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] To replace the cancelled summer 2020 examination series (owing to concerns over the spread of COVID-19), grades were awarded using *centre-assessed grades* and rankings.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] These were initially moderated by Ofqual but, owing to numerous problems, candidates' final grades reverted to those supplied by centres.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] This resulted in significant grade inflation, with initial calculations showing around 37.7% of candidates gaining a grade A or A*, compared with 25.2% in 2019.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In response to concerns shown by employers and universities that it was not possible to distinguish exceptional candidates among the large number of students achieving A grades, and in order to mirror GCSE standards, a higher "super A" grade (like the A* grade at GCSE) was proposed in 2004.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] For modular A2 exams sat from 2010 onwards, the highest A-level grade is A*, requiring an A grade overall and 90% overall average UMS in A2 papers.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The 2004 reform of the Mathematics syllabus, following calls that it was too hard, attracted criticism.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In the change, content consisting of three modules (Pure 1–3) was spread to four modules (Core 1–4).
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It was alleged that this made the course easier as students did less work for the same qualifications.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Further reforms in 2006 to make the Mathematics syllabus more popular were met with mixed opinions.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Supporters cited it would reverse the downward trend in students taking the subject whilst others were concerned that the subject was "still incredibly difficult".
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Examples of concerns were those raised in 2009 by Sir Mike Rake, Chairman of BT Group, Sir Terry Leahy, Chairman of Tesco and by Sir Christopher Gent, Chairman of GlaxoSmithKline.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Some schools have also moved to offering the Cambridge Pre-U as an alternative to A-levels and with higher tariffs.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] With increased modularisation of subjects, the amount of time that young adults are spending being examined in the UK has risen considerably.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It was estimated in a report by educationalists that by the age of 19 children will have spent an entire year of their school education being assessed.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] As a result of such criticisms about the "burden of assessment", since candidates have taken four papers for most A-levels, instead of six as in the past.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] This means that there are two modules for AS and two more for A2 for the majority of A-levels.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] However, this will not be the case for all A-levels: Biology, Human Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Electronics, Geology, Music, Welsh and Science will continue with six units, three units for AS and A2 respectively, and 600 UMS for the A-level.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Mathematics (including Further Mathematics, Additional Further Mathematics, Statistics, and the Use of Mathematics AS), will not change structurally in the modular reform; it will stay on 600 UMS (300 UMS for AS), but it will include the new A* grade and the 'Stretch and Challenge' provision.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Also, Bengali, Modern Hebrew, Punjabi, Polish, Arabic, Japanese, Modern Greek, Biblical Hebrew, Dutch, Gujarati, Persian, Portuguese, and Turkish will remain at two units, one for AS and one for A2.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] However, they will move to 200 UMS for A-level.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Chinese will also move to 200 UMS, but instead of two units, it will move to three units: AS will have two units, A2 will have one.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It is the first A-level to have an odd number of units since Curriculum 2000.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Cambridge University has warned that it is extremely unlikely that it will accept applicants who are taking two or more supposedly 'softer' A-level subjects out of 3.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It has outlined a list of subjects it considers to be 'unsuitable', which includes Accounting, Design and Technology, Film Studies, Information and Communication Technology, Media Studies, Photography, and Sports studies.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] As a result of dislike of the modular system, many schools now offer the alternative International Baccalaureate Diploma qualification.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The course offers more subjects, extracurricular activity, a philosophical epistemological component known as "Theory of Knowledge", as well as the requirement of an extended essay on any subject of a candidate's choice.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Unlike the current AS/A2 system, the International Baccalaureate is not based on a modular system.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The Diploma Programme, administered by the International Baccalaureate, is a recognised pre-university educational programme.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Former British Prime Minister Tony Blair suggested in 2013 that one state school in every county should offer the International Baccalaureate Diploma Programme as an alternative to A-levels.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Maths, Chemistry, or Biology), a language subject (e.g.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] English Language, English Literature, French, German, Spanish), and a "creative" subject (e.g.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Art Studies)—in many cases students choose three closely linked subjects—for example, Mathematics, Physics and Chemistry or Sociology, Psychology, and Politics.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] This is in part due to university entrance requirements, which, for degree programs such as medicine, may require three related A-level subjects, but non-traditional combinations are becoming more common ("British Council Australia Education UK").
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Thus, while the purpose of Curriculum 2000 was to encourage students to undertake contrasting subjects, to broaden their 'skill-base', there is a tendency to pursue similar disciplines.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] However, others disagree, arguing that the additional AS-level(s) studied would already have provided more breadth compared with the old system.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Students applying to universities before receiving their A-level results typically do so on the basis of predicted grades, which are issued by schools and colleges.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A student's predicted grades usually depend on their GCSE results, performance throughout the course, performance in tests and mock examinations, or a combination of these factors.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A possible reformation would be something called the post-qualifications applications system (PQA), where applicants apply to university after they receive their results.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It has been argued that this would be fairer to applicants, especially those from lower-income families whose results were thought to be under-predicted.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] However, a more recent UCAS report shows that although the reliability of predicted grades declines in step with family income, this can still lead to an over-prediction effect for lower income groups.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Just 45% of predicted grades are accurate – 47% are over-predictions and 9% under-predictions.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] A recent UCAS consultation rejected the implementation of PQA following opposition from universities, schools and awarding bodies.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2020 the A-level system was challenged by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Ofqual advised that the 2020 A-level exams should be cancelled, students be given a completion certificate, and universities widen the intake relying on a higher drop-out.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] The government intervened and grades were to be awarded using an algorithm.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] There was a public outcry, explained Roger Taylor the former chair of Ofqual who resigned.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] It was a “colossal error of judgment”: awarding grades calculated by algorithm was not acceptable to the public.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Instead the final grades were awarded by teacher assessment, a system that was repeated in 2021.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Taylor explained the algorithm was robust, it was the way it was being used that caused the problem: that was down to human decisions.
[src:university-college-london/a-level-united-kingdom] Researchers from the London School of Economics and University College London researchers showed that teacher assessment gave a 15% advantage to students with graduate parents.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] It was also, in 1878, the second college in the United Kingdom to admit women alongside men, two years after University College, Bristol, had done so.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] UCL has its main campus in the Bloomsbury area of central London, with a number of institutes and teaching hospitals elsewhere in central London, and has a second campus, UCL East, at Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park in Stratford, East London.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] UCL is organised into 11 constituent faculties, within which there are over 100 departments, institutes and research centres.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] UCL operates several museums and collections in a wide range of fields, including the Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology and the Grant Museum of Zoology and Comparative Anatomy, and administers the annual Orwell Prize in political writing.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] In 2024/25, UCL had a total income of £2.16 billion, of which £556.6 million was from research grants and contracts.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] The university generates around £10 billion annually for the UK economy, primarily through the spread of its research and knowledge (£4 billion) and the impact of its own spending (£3 billion).
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] UCL is a member of numerous academic organisations, including the Russell Group and the League of European Research Universities, and is part of UCL Partners, the world's largest academic health science centre.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] It is considered part of the "golden triangle" of research-intensive universities in southeast England.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] UCL has publishing and commercial activities including UCL Press, UCL Business and UCL Consultants.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] UCL academics discovered five of the naturally occurring noble gases, discovered hormones, invented the vacuum tube, and made several foundational advances in modern statistics.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] As of 2025, 33 Nobel Prize laureates and three Fields Medal recipients have been affiliated with UCL as alumni or academic staff.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] UCL was founded on 11 February 1826 as an alternative to the Anglican universities of Oxford and Cambridge.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] It took the form of a joint stock company, with shares sold for £100 (equivalent to £8,600 in 2025) to proprietors, under the name of *London University*, although without legal recognition as a university or the associated right to award degrees.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] London University's first warden was Leonard Horner, who was the first scientist to head a British university.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] Despite the commonly held belief that the philosopher Jeremy Bentham was the founder of UCL, his direct involvement was limited to the purchase of share No.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] 633, at a cost of £100 paid in nine instalments between December 1826 and January 1830.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] In 1828, he did nominate a friend to sit on the council, and in 1827, attempted to have his disciple John Bowring appointed as the first professor of English or History, but on both occasions his candidates were unsuccessful.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] However, Bentham is commonly regarded as the "spiritual father" of UCL, as his ideas on education and society were influential with the institution's founders, particularly James Mill (1773–1836) and Henry Brougham (1778–1868).
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] In 1828, the chair of political economy at London University was created, with John Ramsay McCulloch as the first incumbent.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] In 1829, the university appointed the first professor of English in England, although the course concentrated on linguistics and the modern teaching of English – studying English literature – was introduced by King's College London in 1831.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] In 1830, London University founded the London University School, which would later become University College School.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] In 1833, the university appointed Alexander Maconochie, secretary to the Royal Geographical Society, as the first professor of geography in Britain.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] Classes in medicine began at the opening of the college in 1828, and in 1834 University College Hospital (originally North London Hospital) opened as a teaching hospital for these classes, which were organised into a faculty of medicine in 1836.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] As a result, the proprietors of London University were incorporated by royal charter under the name *University College, London* on 28 November 1836.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] On the same day, the University of London was created by royal charter as a degree-awarding examining board for students from affiliated schools and colleges, with University College and King's College, London being named in the charter as the first two affiliates.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] The first students from UCL and King's matriculated as undergraduates in 1838 and the first degrees were awarded to students of the two colleges in 1839.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] There had been an intention to establish a course in engineering at the college's opening but no professor was appointed until 1840 or 1841, after engineering courses had started at Durham University (1837) and King's College London (1838).
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] The Slade School of Fine Art was founded as part of University College in 1871, following a bequest from Felix Slade.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] In 1878, the University of London gained a supplemental charter making it the first British university to be allowed to award degrees to women.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] The same year, UCL admitted women to the faculties of Arts and Law and of Science, although women remained barred from the faculties of Engineering and of Medicine (with the exception of courses on public health and hygiene).
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] UCL's admission of women in 1878 came almost three decades after Bedford College became the first institution to offer university-level education for women in Britain, and the establishment of the University of London's General Examination for Women in 1868.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] The Ladies' Educational Association held classes for women from 1868, taught by professors from UCL but independently of the college.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] From 1871 to 1872 these were held inside the college building, although still independently of the college.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] From 1872, some professors, particularly Edward Poynter of the Slade, started to admit women to their classes.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] The full opening on the faculties of arts, science and law in 1878 came two years after the admission of women alongside men at the University of Bristol from its foundation (as University College Bristol) in 1876.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] The first woman to officially enrol in architecture at UCL was Gertrude Leverkus in 1915, although Ethel and Bessie Charles had been allowed to audit classes in the 1890s.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] Women were finally admitted to medical studies during the First World War in 1917, although limitations were placed on their numbers after the war ended.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] A new royal charter granted to the University of London in 1858 effectively removed the affiliation of colleges to the university.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] Dissatisfaction from the colleges and the desire for a "teaching university" in London led to royal commissions that reported in 1888 and 1892 and the reconstitution of the university under the University of London Act 1898.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] Following the University of London's reconstitution in 1900, transforming it from an examining board to a federal university with constituent "schools", UCL became a school of the University of London.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] While most of the colleges that became schools of the university retained their autonomy, UCL chose to be merged into the university in 1907 under the **University College London (Transfer) Act 1905** (5 Edw.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] 7. c. xci) and surrendered its legal independence in return for gaining a greater say in the running of the university.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] Its formal name became *University of London, University College*, although for most informal and external purposes the name "University College, London" (or the initialism UCL) was still used.
[src:university-college-london/university-college-london-p01] As of 2022, it remains listed as "University of London: University College" on US Federal Student Aid applications.
